explanation:
For the MISRA unreachable-code check we need the symbols that determine whether the if-block and the while-loop in OS_ForEachObjectOfType can ever be entered or executed, plus the involved types. Explanations: 

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit: determines the conditional (whether it returns OS_SUCCESS); if it can never return success the entire if-block is unreachable. 
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext: controls the loop condition; its return values determine whether the while body can execute. 
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry: body of the loop calls this; its presence/side-effects are part of reachable code analysis (ensures the call is meaningful and not optimized-away). 
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy: called unconditionally inside the if-block after iteration; needed to determine reachability of that cleanup call. 
- OS_ForEachFilterCreator: function pointer passed into OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit; its signature/behavior may influence iterator initialization and thus reachability. 
- OS_ForEachDoCallback: function pointer passed into OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry; its signature/behavior may influence whether the iterator will invoke processing and affect loop execution. 
- OS_SUCCESS: the constant the initializer is compared against; needed to know the success value and semantics. 
- OS_object_iter_t: iterator type definition is required to understand what OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit/GetNext/etc. operate on and whether any fields force particular behavior. 
- OS_creator_filter_t: filter type definition (fields like creator_id, callbacks) is needed to see how the filter affects iterator initialization/behavior. 
- osal_objtype_t: idtype parameter type (range/valid values) can influence iterator init behavior (e.g., invalid types causing failure). 
- osal_id_t: creator_id type (range/values) can influence initialization success and filtering logic. 
- OS_ArgCallback_t: callback pointer typedef to verify call signatures and whether NULL or certain callbacks affect reachability. 
- OS_GetMaxForObjectType: callee of OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit; its behavior/value can make initialization always fail or succeed. 
- OS_GetBaseForObjectType: callee of OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit; its behavior can affect iterator setup and success/failure. 
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: callee of OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit; its success/failure contributes to iterator init result. 
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: callee of OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy; needed to confirm destroy always executes or can be optimized away.

Providing these symbols (implementations or precise semantics) lets an analyzer decide whether the if condition or while body can ever be reached under any valid inputs, which is necessary to determine violations of the "no unreachable code" rule.
